there!

You did very well in my operating systems class last year.

Proposition: Would you like to TA OS&C in autumn?

TA-ing is an opportunity for you to immerse yourself even further in this area; you learn the most by teaching to others.

Application deadline is coming up, maybe end of April? (I can't see any listing) (if you miss the deadline, but still want to TA, then let me know, and I'll try to fix that). I have space for up to 7 TAs in the course.

To entice you: I'm making a few changes to the course that you might like:

1) Reorder & Trim lectures.
2) Redesign labs.
3) C first, C throughout the course.

***

1)
When I took over the course in 2022, osc22 was essentially a course on (non-modern) computer architecture, with some performance, all at a high level; there was very little on low-level details, on actual operating systems, and on security (all of which are crucial today). I have been addressing this issue over the years, gradually reworking and reorganizing the course by reducing & removing topics to accommodate modern computer architecture, operating systems, and security. (*)

In osc24, the list of topics was close to ideal. But there were two outstanding issues. i) The course was (still) bottom-up, meaning operating systems come late in the course. Consequence: students get a "whole picture" of computer systems very late (which hurts learning). ii) There is a bit too much content in the course. Consequence: it is too hard to follow and keep track of all the material; students easily get lost.

To address pt. i, I'll focus on a "vertical slice" of computer systems first, presenting only the hardware, assembly, and C, needed to present core operating system concepts: memory management, processes, threads, locks (1970s hardware; single-core CPU, MMU, PIC). Next we add more modern hardware features (pipelining, caching, multicore, etc.) to switch focus to performance (easier since hardware was introduced weeks ago). Lastly, we switch focus to security (overflows, monitors, isolation) (easier since operating system was introducecd weeks ago).

To address pt. ii, I am reducing the level of detail in which the following are covered in the course: pipelining, SIMD, and CUDA. I will only present the "hello, world!" of these, and I will not have labs on these. (I will consider re-adding these details/labs to the course once the course is more polished).

(*) : It was during this process I decided to part ways with the CSApp book; while great, it is not a good fit for what OS&C needs to be; CSApp is a bit outdated, and goes into way too much detail with number representation & assembly (360 pages), and microarchitecture (150 pages), which leaves little room to cover other topics. Supplementing Dive Into Systems turns out to be much easier.

2)
The above changes mean the current labs do not make as much sense. Furthermore, students felt they had too little assembly and C experience before doing the labs. Consequently, I am updating the labs to match the new course structure (see below).

3)
In osc24, I delayed coverage of C back to what osc22 and earlier did, to talk about hardware at a lower level of abstraction. This turned out to make it harder for students to do labs, as they had seen C too little when they reached the labs. In osc23, C came sooner, and I received no such feedback. I am therefore making C the second lecture. Since Assembly is the first lecture, this gives us a choice of low- and high-level language to explain things.

Finally, by presenting C early, I can use C when producing demos of hardware features at work. It is my hope to show C code and C demos in each lecture, to make sure nothing is too abstract, and so students see how what is being taught makes a difference in apps.

***

Here is the outline for osc25 so far:

1. Assembly     (ELF, linking, stack, heap, malloc, debugging, no overflows)
2. C            (C-to-Assembly: procedures, types, struct, pointers, ...)
   Lab: "clab"  (osc23's clab + assembly, malloc, valgrind (Jim Huang) )
3. Architecture (CPU+MMU+PIC, ISA, SEQ, addr. translation, x86 interrupt system)
4. Processes    (process, thread, scheduling, concurrency issues, atomics, lock)
5. I/O          (memory (malloc, mmap), file (read, write), socket (bind, ...))
   Lab: "oslab" (borrow from OSTEP; implement e.g. OS scheduing in xv6)
6. Locality     (memory hierarchy, caching, paging (TLB), prefetching)
7. Parallelism  (PIPE (?) (hazards), SIMD, multicore (cache coherence), CUDA)
   <autumn break>
8. Optimization (loop unrolling, branchless programming, false sharing, etc.)
   Lab: "prflab"(remove blend_v, improve compiler optimization (less ad hoc))
9. Safety       (undefined behavior, overflows, format string violation, etc.)
A. Verification (eBPF)
B. Monitoring   (DAC (user/group), LSM, MAC (seLINUX))
Lab: "seclab"   (overflows, use-after-free, double unlock, more?)
C. Containment  (chroot, cgroups, namespaces, capabilities, seccomp, etc.)
D.
E. Exam brief
<christmas break>
<exam>
<re-exam>

You will receive complete solutions to the labs before they are released to the students, so you can prepare to help the students.

Labs are autograded, although I am considering asking TAs to do a light code review, rejecting submissions that have no/poor explanations in source code. To incentivize students to produce quality submissions & to understand them, I have added a snydtjek to labs.

Må vi se slides ð

Men generelt var udmeldingen at de syntes vores slides var forvirrende og de kunne ikke rigtig se at vi havde brugt nogen af modellerne ud fra dem, så tror også der lagt meget fokus i teori omkring det. Der var ingen spørgsmål omkring disruption og patterns, men havde vi også alle med i vores individuelle så kan være derfor

Så var der flere steder hvor der blev taget udgangspunkt i vores slides. Natalie blev bedt om at forklare hvordan man finder kunde segmenter, svaret var customer profile, så forklarere hun hvordan man lavede den, og blev så ført hen til vores slutkundeprofil og skulle så udpege et funktionelt, emotionelt, og socialt job fra den og herefter beskrive ud fra vores kilder hvor meget vi kunne stole på dem

Alle blev bedt om at have en styrke, en svaghed og en forklaring på hvordan ens forslag afhjalp dette klar. Så man nævnte en competitor man havde sammenlignet sit firma med, også en styrke i ens firma og en svaghed - også forklaret kort hvordan ens forslag gjorde noget ved det

Daniel blev bedt om efter at have forklaret hypoteser og hvad diskret, præcis og testable betød, så at analysere en af hans egne hypoteser og lave den om så den passede til teorien.

Performance assessment - vi blev nærmest bedt om at nævne et af de spørgsmål man bruger til det sådan som jeg forstod det. Men forklaringen var at performance assessment bruges til at vurdere ens firma i forhold til end konkurrenter og at hvert spørgsmål er til hver blok i bmc.

Trend assessment - svaret værende hvordan det adskilte sig fra performance, altså at man her vurderer hvordan ens firma vil klare sig i fremtiden i forhold til trends - trends kan stadig ramme hver enkelt blok i bmc

2. Installer `ripgrep` -> sudo apt install ripgrep

Det er så vigtigt at sige her, at den arkitektur som Alberts eksempel har ikke har "variable length instructions", dvs. alle instruktioner er 4 bytes nøjagtigt. Du skal huske ikke bare at increment 4 bytes :D

Tak! giver mening, var mest forvirret over om jeg skulle incremente adressen i hex format i opgaven, altså om man bare kunne sige 0x100, 0x110, osv eller om jeg skulle converte decimal, lægge bytes til offsettet, i decimal, og så converte det om til hex igen
@Emilie her er et eksempel på hvordan det ser ud i en rigtig binary. Start adressen her er 0x0000000100003f70 og så kan du se ud fra hver linje hvordan start adressen incrementeres.
Den der forkortes med CSAPP
Håber det giver mening
Jeg finder lige et eksempel senere. Du kan prøve at lave en objdump på en binær fil og kigge på offsets i forhold til starten.

Den måde mange instruktionssæt fungerer på er, at de gerne vil have et lille segment til data, som f.eks. strings.

Ãrsagen til at der findes det her "0x100" offset, er så der kan ligge data inden. Det er egentligt bare, at du hopper til 0x100th index i "filen". 

"loop" er det som hedder et label, og det er en "makro" for en adresse i memory. Den bliver udregnet når "instruktionerne" bliver kompileret. 

Dvs. det er 0x100 + offset mellem det og starten af "loop" adressen, som ville være antal bytes derop
